TreeMap in Java

TreeMap is a class in Java that implements the Map interface.

It stores data as key → value pairs, but unlike HashMap, it keeps keys sorted.

How TreeMap works

TreeMap is based on a Red-Black Tree (self-balancing binary search tree).

👉 This means:

keys are always sorted
operations stay efficient
Key Features
keys are sorted
no null keys ❌
values can be null ✅
not thread-safe
slower than HashMap
Creating a TreeMap
import java.util.TreeMap;
import java.util.Map;

Map<String, Integer> map = new TreeMap<>();
Example
map.put("Banana", 2);
map.put("Apple", 1);
map.put("Orange", 3);

System.out.println(map);

👉 Output:

{Apple=1, Banana=2, Orange=3}
Sorting Rules
Default (Natural Order)
numbers → ascending
strings → alphabetical
Custom Sorting (Comparator)
Map<String, Integer> map = new TreeMap<>(
    (a, b) -> b.compareTo(a)
);

👉 reverse order

Common Methods
put(), get(), remove()
map.put("Apple", 1);
map.get("Apple");
map.remove("Apple");
First and Last Keys
map.firstKey();
map.lastKey();
Navigational Methods
map.higherKey("Apple");  // next key
map.lowerKey("Apple");   // previous key
map.ceilingKey("Apple"); // >= key
map.floorKey("Apple");   // <= key
Performance
Operation	Complexity
put()	O(log n)
get()	O(log n)
remove()	O(log n)

👉 slower than HashMap, but keeps order

TreeMap vs HashMap
Feature	TreeMap	HashMap
Order	Sorted	No order
Speed	O(log n)	O(1)
Null key	❌	✅
Use case	Sorted data	Fast lookup
When to use TreeMap

Use it when:

you need sorted keys
you need range queries
order matters
When NOT to use
when performance is critical → use HashMap
when sorting is not needed
Summary
TreeMap stores sorted key-value pairs
based on Red-Black Tree
operations are O(log n)
useful when order matters
